🔒  SECTION 12: SECURITY & SYSTEM HARDENING
Rate limiting, injection protection, secrets management, horizontal scaling, and caching

12.1 Security Layers Overview
Layer	Tool / Method	What It Protects Against
HTTP Headers	helmet	Clickjacking, XSS, MIME sniffing, content injection
CORS	cors (whitelist only)	Unauthorized domains calling your API
Rate Limiting	express-rate-limit	Brute force attacks, DDoS, API abuse
NoSQL Injection	express-mongo-sanitize	MongoDB operator injection via req.body
Parameter Pollution	hpp	HTTP parameter pollution attacks
JWT Security	jsonwebtoken + httpOnly cookies	Token theft, XSS token stealing
Secrets Management	.env + Docker secrets	API keys never in codebase or Docker image
Input Validation	zod / joi	Malformed request bodies crashing the server
File Upload Safety	Multer type + size checks	Malicious file uploads, oversized payloads
MongoDB Security	Atlas IP whitelist + auth	Unauthorized database access

12.2 Express Security Setup
Apply these in app.js before any route is registered:

import helmet               from 'helmet';
import cors                 from 'cors';
import mongoSanitize        from 'express-mongo-sanitize';
import hpp                  from 'hpp';
import rateLimit            from 'express-rate-limit';

// 1. Security headers
app.use(helmet());

// 2. CORS — only allow your frontend domain
app.use(cors({ origin: process.env.FRONTEND_URL, credentials: true }));

// 3. Global rate limit — 100 requests per 15 min per IP
app.use(rateLimit({ windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, max: 100 }));

// 4. NoSQL injection protection
app.use(mongoSanitize());

// 5. HTTP parameter pollution
app.use(hpp());

// 6. Body size limit — prevent large payload attacks
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));

12.3 JWT Security — httpOnly Cookies
Never store JWT in localStorage — it is vulnerable to XSS. Always use httpOnly cookies:

// After Google OAuth success — set cookie, not response body
res.cookie('braudle_token', jwtToken, {
  httpOnly: true,      // JS cannot read this cookie
  secure:   true,      // HTTPS only in production
  sameSite: 'strict',  // CSRF protection
  maxAge:   7 * 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000  // 7 days
});

// Auth middleware reads from cookie
const token = req.cookies.braudle_token;
const decoded = jwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT_SECRET!);

12.4 Environment Secrets — Never In Code
Rule	Why
Never commit .env to Git — add to .gitignore immediately	Leaked secrets expose your entire system
Use .env.example with placeholder values only — commit this	Lets developers know what vars are needed without exposing values
In Docker — pass env vars at runtime, never bake into image	Docker images can be inspected — never embed secrets in layers
In production — use Railway / Render / AWS Secrets Manager	Encrypted secret storage, not plain .env files on a server
Rotate GROQ_API_KEY and JWT_SECRET every 90 days	Limits exposure window if a key is ever compromised

12.5 Rate Limiting Strategy — All Endpoints
Endpoint Group	Limit	Window	Purpose
All endpoints (global)	100 requests	15 minutes per IP	General DDoS/abuse protection
POST /api/auth/google/callback	20 requests	15 minutes per IP	Prevent OAuth brute force
POST /api/documents/upload	Type-specific	24 hours (per userId)	2 PDF / 5 Image per day
POST /api/sessions/chat	60 requests	1 minute per user	Prevent AI API cost abuse
POST /api/quiz/generate	10 requests	1 hour per user	Prevent quiz spam

12.6 Caching Strategy (Redis)
Redis is already running for BullMQ. Use the same instance for caching:

What to Cache	Cache Key	TTL	Why
Document chunks after processing	chunks:{documentId}	24 hours	Avoid re-reading MongoDB on every teach request
Student profile (level, weak topics)	profile:{userId}	10 minutes	Profile is read on every session — cache reduces DB load
Quiz questions after generation	quiz:{sessionId}	1 hour	Avoid regenerating quiz if student refreshes page
Rate limit counters	ratelimit:{userId}:{date}	24 hours	Fast in-memory check without hitting MongoDB

12.7 Horizontal Scaling
When BRAUDLE grows and one server isn't enough, scale horizontally using this strategy:

Component	Scaling Strategy	How
Express API	Stateless — scale to multiple instances	Docker replicas behind a load balancer (Nginx / AWS ALB)
MongoDB	MongoDB Atlas auto-scaling	Atlas handles replica sets and sharding automatically
Redis	Redis Cluster or Redis Cloud	Shared cache and queue state across all API instances
BullMQ Workers	Spin up more worker containers	Each worker pulls from the same Redis queue — no coordination needed
File Storage	S3 / Cloudflare R2	Already distributed — no scaling needed
Next.js Frontend	Vercel (auto-scales)	Deploy to Vercel — zero config scaling

KEY INSIGHT	Because the Express API is stateless (JWT auth, Redis for session/cache, MongoDB Atlas for data), you can add more API containers at any time with zero code changes. The load balancer distributes traffic automatically.
 
